Homework 5: Plotting

Solution

Reading

  1. Please read Chapter 3 of R4DS. This is a really nice reference. If youre interested, look at section 3.7 for a deeper understanding of how different statistical transformations can be accommodated within different geometries in ggplot2.

Exercises

  1. Lets look at the breast cancer data set webe been using.

    1. Create a bar plot of the frequencies of ER status (Hint: geom_bar. How would you modify the dataset so that there is no separate bar for NAs?

      library(tidyverse)
library(rio)
brca <- import('data/clinical_data_breast_cancer_hw.csv')
brca <- brca %>% filter(ER.Status != 'Indeterminate')
ggplot(brca, aes(x = ER.Status))+geom_bar()

    2. Color each bar by the frequencies of HER2 status within each group. (Hint: you can add aes(color='HER2.Status') or aes(fill='HER2.Status') to the geom_bar statement. What is the difference in these two choices?)

      ggplot(brca, aes(x = ER.Status)) + geom_bar(aes(fill=HER2.Final.Status))

    3. I would like to see a graph showing the relative frequencies of HER2 status within each ER group. Read the documentation ?geom_bar as well as section 3.8 of R4DS to find this solution.

      ggplot(brca, aes(x = ER.Status)) + geom_bar(aes(fill=HER2.Final.Status), position='fill')

  2. The diamonds dataset is included in the ggplot2 package.

    1. Add a column to the diamonds dataset that is the volume of each diamond (multiplying the x, y and z variables)

      mydiamonds <- diamonds %>% 
  mutate(vol = x*y*z)

    2. Plot a scatter plot of diamond price against diamond volume

      ggplot(mydiamonds, aes(x =vol, y = price)) + geom_point()

    3. Modify the plot to add colors based on the cut of each diamond

      ggplot(mydiamonds, aes(x =vol, y = price, color=cut)) + geom_point()

    4. Modify the previous plot to construct a facetted plot where each facet is based on a color.

      ggplot(mydiamonds, aes(x = vol, y = price))+
  geom_point()+
  facet_wrap(~color)

Extra credit

The breast cancer expression dataset contains log-expression levels of 10 probes for the same individuals that are in the clinical dataset.

  1. Modify the dataset appropriately and draw a facetted plot where each facet is a histogram of the expression levels of each probe.
brca_expression <- import('data/BreastCancer_Expression.xlsx')
brca_expression %>% gather(probe, expression, starts_with('NP')) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = expression))+geom_histogram()+
  facet_wrap(~probe)
